FBIS4-63621 "drsov100_b_94019" FBIS-SOV-94-100 Daily Report 23 May 1994 RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS Economic Issues Yeltsin Signs Edict on Collection of Taxes, Duties Yeltsin Signs Edict on Collection of Taxes, Duties LD2305172894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1617 GMT 23 May 94 LD2305172894 Moscow INTERFAX English BFN [Text] According to a decree on complex measures to ensure prompt and entire collection of taxes and duties signed by Russian President Boris Yeltsin Monday, all taxpayers will have to register in the State Taxation Service. The decree stipulates that taxpayers may open accounts with banks only if they have been properly registered. If an enterprise violates the procedure, it will be administratively imposed a fine of one hundred minimum salaries. At the moment, the minimum salary in Russia is 14,700 rubles. In case of a repeated violation, the taxation service reports it to the Central Bank of Russia. The tax evader will be abolished and its incomes confiscated by the treasury. According to the decree, a taxpayer may have one current and one budget accounts with a bank for his operations within the scope of his activities. Taxpayers must submit information on their open accounts, including hard currency, loans, deposits both in Russia and abroad. The decree came into force once signed.
